Justification notes2: The last confirmed specimen was collected off Long Island, New York, in 1875 (or possibly 1878) (BirdLife International 2011).
The species was last seen alive in 1902. By the time the first Auckland Islands reserve was set up in 1910, it was extinct (Tennyson and Martinson 2006).

The species was last recorded in 1860. Reports of unidentifiable nightjars from its habitat in the 1980s have led to suggestions that may still be extant, and there is a possibility that surveys may have overlooked this cryptic, nocturnal species (BirdLife International 2011). Therefore it is best considered Critically Endangered (Possibly Extinct).

The species is only known from the type specimen, which Brace collected in 1877. It is likely to have gone extinct around this time, because collectors visiting the island soon afterwards found no trace of it (Graves and Olson 1987).
The species is known only from the type specimen collected in 1860 (BirdLife International 2011).

The species has not been recorded since the 19th century, with an unconfirmed report in 1976 and no subsequent records despite a specific search in 1980 (BirdLife International 2011). The habitat at the type locality has been destroyed, but the distribution of the species is uncertain. It is likely to be extinct, but further searches are required to confirm this. It is therefore best treated as Critically Endangered (Possibly Extinct).
The last known pair were killed on Eldey I, Iceland, in 1844, and the last live bird was seen off the Newfoundland Banks in 1852 (BirdLife International 2011).
Last seen 1940
The species was last collected in 1913 and locally reported to have become extinct by the 1940s (BirdLife International 2011).

Survived until 1960s. Last survival Stewart I, New Zealand. Only two snipe were found after the accidental introduction of black rats (Rattus rattus) onto the subspecies's final refuge on Stewart Island in 1964. Both were taken into captivity but died soon after (Tennyson and Martinson 2006).

The last irrefutable record is of a specimen collected in Barbados in 1963. There have been numerous unconfirmed reports since, especially between 1981 and 2006, and so the species is best considered Critically Endangered (Possibly Extinct) (BirdLife International 2011).
Became extinct in early 19C

Formerly a subspecies of T. varius, it has not been seen since 1912 and is (since 2010) usually treated as a full species. The last known individual was taken by Saracin in 1912. Warner's surveys were unsuccessful (Warner 1947), as was more recent fieldwork (Ekstrom et al. 2002), though as neither were comprehensive it is best considered Critically Endangered (Possibly Extinct).
It was reported to still be present by Desjardins (1832), but was extinct by the mid-1930s (Cheke 1987).
The species has not been recorded since a specimen was taken in 1927. Surveys, the first of which was in 1995, have been unsuccessful in relocating it (BirdLife International 2011).

The species is only known from the type specimen, collected sometime between 1783 and 1823. It is thought to have come from Tahiti, based on local accounts from 1928 which match the description of the species (BirdLife International 2011).

It was last seen on the Daito Islands in 1936. In the 1960s it was believed to possibly survive on isolated islets, but it there have been no further sightings and it is clearly extinct (Brazil 1991).
The species was last recorded in 1889 (BirdLife International 2011).

The last reliable specimen came from Ohio in 1900. A two-year search was carried out beginning in 1910, to determine whether the species was extinct in the wild. It found no evidence for its persistence (Blockstein and Tordoff 1985). The last captive bird died in 1914 in the Cincinnati Zoo (BirdLife International 2011).
The species was last recorded in 1904. Reports from the 1940s are not thought to be accurate. It is now considered Extinct (BirdLife International 2011).

At least 11 specimens are known, the last of which was collected by the Whitney Expedition in 1922 (Holyoak and Thibault 1984). Reports from Hiva Oa in 1980 were presumably mistaken (Collar et al. 1994).
The last sighting in the wild was in 1972 (BirdLife International 2011).
The taxon has been extinct in the wild since 1986, when 29 birds were taken for captive breeding (Woodall 2001).

The taxon became extinct around 1922 (Thibault 1973, Holyoak and Thibault 1977, 1984, Seitre and Seitre 1991, 1992, Woodall 2001). A report from the 2000s is not considered to be accurate (P. Raust in litt. 2011).
It has not been reported since 1834 (Morris and Hawkins 1998).
It was last recorded in 1903, and is now extinct (Barton et al. 2004).
The most recent reports in the wild were of individuals hunted in 1984 and 1988 (del Hoyo 1994).
The last record was from around 1875, thought to represent the last individual of the species (Tennyson and Martinson 2006).
The last confirmed live birds were found in 1893. It was extinct by 1895 (Tennyson and Martinson 2006).

Recent evidence, including a letter from Dannefarerd to Rothschild in 1895 describing the species's appearance, behaviour and the Moriori hunting method, suggests that this species survived into at least the late 1800s (BirdLife International 2011).
Reports from the Challenger expedition of 1873 suggest it was extant (Beintema 1972), but villagers contacted on the Valhalla expedition in 1906 said it was no longer present (Nicoll 1906).
Already scarce when the type specimen was collected in 1840, the species was extinct by 1872 (BirdLife International 2011).
The species was extirpated from the wild in 1987 (BirdLife International 2011).
It was last recorded from Mehetia in the 1930s (Taylor and Van Perlo 1998).
It is known from 12 specimens from Vitu Levu and Ovalau collected in the 19th century, and reports from Taveuni in 1971 and Vitu Levu in 1973 (BirdLife International 2011).

Former distribution: Wake I, United States Minor Outlying Islands
Justification notes2: It has not been seen since 1945. Thomas D. Musson, a resident of the island from 1946-1949, never saw the species (Greenway 1967).
Not uncommon when discovered in 1790, this species had probably already vanished by the time the island was colonised in 1834 (BirdLife International 2011).
The species is known from subfossils from a number of archaeological sites, and from one possible 1894 record (BirdLife International 2011).

The species is known from illustrations by Miller from 1784 (although these are sometimes considered to refer to Spotless Crake), and it presumably became extinct soon after this (BirdLife International 2011).

The population on Laysan became extinct between 1923 and 1936. Black rats (Rattus rattus), brought in by wartime activities, exterminated the introduced populations on Sand Island in 1943 and Eastern Island in 1944 (BirdLife International 2011).
The last specimen was collected in 1864, and the last report was in 1884 (or possibly 1893) (BirdLife International 2011).
The species was extinct by November 1895, but it had survived into that year, with Travers finding a cat-caught specimen in February (Tennyson and Martinson 2006).
The taxon was last recorded in 1972 (Collar et al. 1994).
Abundant in 1928, but the species could not be found on a visit in 1936 and has not been seen since (Hindwood 1940).
Not seen since c. 1960.

Population on both islands became extinct in 19C. It was collected by Garrett in the 1870s (Cibois et al. 2008), but the Whitney Expedition found none in 1922 (Kennerley and Pearson 2010). Formerly recognized only as a ssp of A. caffer.
Not seen since 1995. Originally thought to be a ssp of Guam RW

Thought to have been extinct at least since the late 1970s. Formerly considered a subspecies of Guam RW. Became extinct on Pagan, to which it was confined, before 1981 (Bairlein et al. 2006). Local people stated that it persisted until the 1960s, but intensive searches in the late 1970s and early 1980s confirmed its extinction (Tenorio et al. 1979, Reichel et al. 1992).
The last records were in 1983; intensive searches in 1986 confirmed that the species was extinct (BirdLife International 2011).
The taxon was last recorded in 1967 (Clout and Hay 1981).
The last confirmed record dates from 1907 (BirdLife International 2011).

Authority: Mahood, Eames, Oliveros, Moyle, Chamnan, Poole, Nielsen & Sheldon, 2013

Justification notes2: The last two wild individuals were recorded in 2002 but did not return to their breeding site in 2003 (BirdLife International 2011).

Known from only two specimens collected in 1837 (Olson and James 1995) and undocumented reports in 1937 and 1940 (Greenway 1967). These reports are not generally considered accurate and the taxon likely died out in the 1800s (E. VanderWerf in litt. 2011).
The last report was in 1940 on Big Island (BirdLife International 2011).

The taxon was last recorded in 1969 (Olson and James 1995), around which time it is thought to have gone extinct (E. VanderWerf in litt. 2011). Intensive surveys since have failed to find it (Gorresen et al. 2009).
It was last recorded in 1828. Local rumours that it persisted until the 1890s were never substantiated (Brazil 1991).
The species was last collected in 1894 on Lana‘i (BirdLife International 2011).
It has not been found since a specimen was collected in 1892 on Big Island (Greenway 1967). There is a possible but unlikely record from 1937 (Munro 1960).
It was last collected in 1907 on Lana‘i. Searches since then failed to find it, and it was considered extinct by 1949 (BirdLife International 2011).
The species was last recorded in 1898 (BirdLife International 2011).

The taxon has not been certainly recorded since Perkins collected it in 1896 (Munro 1960). Research in 1994–1996 only yielded one possible sighting (Reynolds and Snetsinger 2001). Pratt (2010) suggests a few recent reports seem credible, but Pratt and Pyle (2000) are sceptical of all 20th century records.

Two were taken in 1899 by Munro (1960), who doubts it has been seen since. There were unconfirmed reports in 1960 and 2007 (Pratt 2010). Intensive searches in the 1990s were unsuccessful (Pratt and Pyle 2000).
Perkins found evidence that many existed in the forests of Oahu in 1860, but  no collectors found any trace of it in the 1890s (Munro 1960).

Three were seen by Wetmore when he arrived on Laysan in 1923 (Munro 1960). This is widely accepted as the date of extinction, as the birds were not seen following a sandstorm later that year, and have never been seen since (E. VanderWerfin litt. 2011).
Last reported in 1988. Searches in the 1990s were inconclusive, with possible audio evidence obtained (Pratt 2010), amd in light of this it is considered Critically Endangered (Possibly Extinct).
The last convincing report dates from 1930 (Donaghho 1963). It is considered extinct by Pratt (2005).

One of the last three known individuals in the wild was taken into care in September 2004, but it died in November 2004. The other two birds hadnot been seen on Maui since December 2003 and February 2004 respectively (BirdLife International 2011).
The last sightings were between 1961 and 1963 on Moloka‘i. The Hawaiian Forest Bird Survey beginning in 1979 failed to find the species, and there have been no records since (Gorresen et al. 2009).
The last well-documented observation of this species was in 1985, with a reasonably convincing, but unconfirmed, record in 1990 (BirdLife International 2011).
The species has not been recorded with certainty on Kaua‘i since 1989 nor on Big Island since 1987 (BirdLife International 2011).
Specimens were collected on Big Island in 1891, but Perkins did not find the bird in 1893 and it has not been seen since (Greenway 1967).
The last specimens were taken onBig Island in 1896, and ten years later it could not be found by Henshaw (BirdLife International 2011).
The specoes was last recorded in 1901 on Big Island (BirdLife International 2011).
Not seen since 2011

Authority: Krabbe, Agro, Rice, Jacome, Navarrete & Sornoza, 1999

Justification notes2: The species was last recorded in 1910, and presumably became extinct soon after (BirdLife International 2011).

Authority: Eames, Le Trong Trai, Nguyen Cu & Eve, 1999
Alström, Xia, Rasmussen, Olsson, Dai, Zhao, Leader, Carey, Dong, Cai, Holt, Manh, Song, Liu, Zhang & Lei, 2015

Justification notes2: The last record was from around 1892, when the species is thought to have become extinct (Tennyson and Martinson 2006).

Authority: Hosner, Boggess, Alviola, Sánchez-González, Oliveros, Urriza & Moyle, 2013

Justification notes2: It was last recorded in 1906 on Little Mangere. An expedition in 1938 hoping to rediscover the species found no trace of it (Tennyson and Martinson 2006).
The last specimen was collected in 1859 (BirdLife International 2011).
The species has not been recorded since 1837. None of the collectors visiting O‘ahu between 1890 and 1900 found any trace of it (Greenway 1967).
It was last recorded in 1981 and considered extinct by 2001 (BirdLife International 2011).
The last report, of vocalisations, came from 1987. Surveys since have been unsuccessful and it was considered extinct by 1998 (BirdLife International 2011).
The species was last seen in 1934 on Lana‘i (BirdLife International 2011).
Common in forest until the 1970s, this species plummeted to extinction in 1983 (BirdLife International 2011).
The species was last recorded in 1977, and 10 years later a survey failed to find it (Thibault and Meyer 2001). It has not been seen since.

The last confirmed record dates from 1985, and searches in 1989, 1990 and 1998 failed to find the species (Thibault and Meyer 2001). However, a possible report from 2010 has raised hopes that the species may still survive, with follow-up searches planned for 2012 (P. Raust in litt. 2011). In light of this, although the species was considered Extinct on the 2011 IUCN Red List (BirdLife International 2011), we treat it as Critically Endangered (Possibly Extinct) here.
It was last recorded in the 1930s and has not been seen in several surveys since, the first being in 1972 (Thibault and Meyer 2001).

Authority: Duckworth, Alström, Davidson, Evans, et al., 2001

Justification notes2: The taxon was last recorded in 1905, when it was said to be ‘fast expiring’. There have been only dubious sightings since (Tennyson and Martinson 2006).

The genus Turnagra is included in Oriolidae following Johansson et al. (2011). The last substantiated record of this species was a specimen shot in 1902. There have been unconfirmed reports since, but none since around 1970 (Tennyson and Martinson 2006).

The last confirmed records came from near Charleston, South Carolina in 1958-1961. Specific searches in 1975-1979 failed to find the species (Hamel 2011), but there have been unconfirmed reports since and it is best treated as Critically Endangered (Possibly Extinct) until its entire potential habitat has been surveyed (BirdLife International 2011).

Authority: (Alström, Davidson, Duckworth, Eames, Le, Nguyen, Olsson, Robson & Timmins, 2009)
Nachtigall Maurício, Belmonte-Lopes, Pacheco, Silveira, Whitney & Bornschein, 2014
Avendaño, Cuervo, López, Gutiérrez Pinto, Cortés & Cadena, 2015
Krabbe, Salaman, Cortés, Quevedo, Ortega & Cadena, 2005

Justification notes2: Known from two specimens collected in 1828, this species was extinct by the time Finsch visited the island in 1880 (BirdLife International 2011).

The Lord Howe subspecies has not been seen since 1918 (Hindwood 1940). A search in 1928 found none (Sharland 1929).The Norfolk subspecies has not been seen since 1923 (Garnett 1992), but its absence was noted only in 1968 (Smithers and Disney 1969).

The species is known only from its type specimen, collected in 1825. The island was not visited by ornithologists until nearly 150 years later, by which time it had become extinct (BirdLife International 2011).
The last specimen was shot in 1837, and the species became extinct between 1850 and 1860 (BirdLife International 2011).

Authority: Whitney, M.L. Isler, Bravo, Aristizábal, Schunck, L.F. Silveira, Piacentini, Cohn-Haft & M.A. Rêgo, 2013

Justification notes2: Considered by many to be an abnormal collection of Sporophila nigricollis. The species is only known from the type, which was collected in 1823 on the banks of Rio Araguaia. Searches of the river's floodplain in 2008 and 2009 found no evidence of the species, but more comprehensive surveys would be required to confirm its extinction and so it is best considered Critically Endangered (Possibly Extinct) (BirdLife International 2011).

Authority: Salaman, Coopmans, Donegan, Mulligan, Cortés, Hilty & Ortega, 2003

Justification notes2: There were a few reports in the 1980s (Collar 2005) of the Mayotte subspecies and it was last accurately recorded in 1994 (Clement and Hathway 2000). Most of its range was surveyed after without success, but Kamako‘u Peak and Oloku‘i have still not been explored (Reynolds and Snetsinger 2001). Until those sites have been surveyed, it is best considered Critically Endangered (Possibly Extinct). The type subspecies was last seen on Lana‘i in 1933 (Collar 2005), which is suggested as a likely extinction date by Clement and Hathway (2000).

The last confirmed sighting of the species was in 1985. Unconfirmed reports continued until 1991, but the lack of confirmed records despite intensive and targeted searches in 1995 and 1997, make it appropriate to classify this species as Extinct (BirdLife International 2011).
The last specimen was collected in 1911, with the last sight record in 1938. It was extinct by 1965 (Bradley 2000).

Authority: Alström, Rasmussen, Zhao, Xu, Dalvi, Cai, Guan, Zhang, Kalyakin, Lei & Olsson, 2016

Justification notes2: Known from four specimens collected in 1828, this species could not be found when the island was next visited by an ornithologist, in 1889 (BirdLife International 2011).
Last reliable record in 1987. Formerly considered a ssp of P. rubinus.

It has not been certainly recorded since 1979. Formal searches have failed to find any over the last two decades, although there have been scattered reports throughout this time (BirdLife International 2011). Despite being considered Critically Endangered currently by BirdLife International (2011), it is treated as Critically Endangered (Possibly Extinct) here on the basis of unsuccessful surveys in 2010 (G. C. L. Dutson in litt. 2011).

Often regarded as conspecific with Z. saypanii (extant). The most recent sighting was in June 1983 at Pajon Basin (Van Balen 2008). There is no reasonable doubt that it is now extinct (G. C. L. Dutson in litt. 2011).
Abbott took specimens of the subspecies in 1892 (Ridgway 1895). It probably went extinct around 1900, and certainly by 1940 (Penny 1974).
The species was common in 1908 (Hull 1909), but could not be found in 1928 (Sharland 1929).
The species was last recorded in the 1890s (Tennyson and Martinson 2006) and was extinct by 1900 (BirdLife International 2011).

Authority: O'Neill, Lane, Kratter, Capparella et al., 2000

Justification notes2: The last confirmed record was from Durango in 1956 but there have been several convincing local reports of sightings since 1965.Although it has been searched for extensively, it remains possible that individuals persist (BirdLife International 2011) and so it is best treated as Critically Endangered (Possibly Extinct).
The last confirmed record was in 1977, and intensive studies in 1981 and 1982 failed to find the species (BirdLife International 2011).
The species was reduced to 30 individuals by 1983 and was extinct by 1986 (BirdLife International 2011).

The last confirmed report of the species was in 1985. By 2009, all wetlands where it could feasibly survive had been surveyed, leaving no reasonable doubt that the last individual had died (BirdLife International 2011).

The last confirmed report was of a breeding bird seen in 1912. Surveys in 1922 confirmed it is probably extinct (BirdLife International 2011), but because of the difficulties associated with tracking nocturnal petrels, and the suitable conditions that remain on the island, it could survive and is best treated as Critically Endangered (Possibly Extinct).

Authority: (Bolton, A.L. Smith, E. Gomez-Diaz, V.L. Friesen, R. Medeiros, J. Bried, J.L. Roscales & R.W. Furness, 2008)
Harrison, Sallaberry, Gaskin, Baird, Jamarillo, Metz, Pearman, O'Keeffe, Dowdall, Enright, Fahy, Gilligan & Lillie, 2013

Justification notes2: Last collected in 1879 and may have been driven extinct around 1936 due to hunting for food and predation by mongooses (Haynes-Sutton et al. 2009). However, nocturnal petrels are notoriously difficult to detect and without further comprehensive searches the species is best considered Critically Endangered (Possibly Extinct).
Formerly widely distributed. No confirmed sighting since the 1980s

The species was last collected in 1864, with the last reports in 1885. A number of other related species (additional to those mentioned here) have been described from the West Indies, but are not based on sound evidence (BirdLife International 2011).
No confirmed sightings since early 20C but unconfirmed sightings suggest it may have survived until 1976

Former distribution: S. USA. Subspecies of the Louisiana region, USA, last to go extinct
Justification notes2: The last bird of the Louisiana subspecies is thought to have died around 1910 (BirdLife International 2011).

The last known individual in the wild disappeared at the end of 2000. However, it cannot yet be presumed to be extinct in the wild until all possible habitat has been surveyed (BirdLife International 2011).
In 1894 no birds had been reported for two years. The last definitive record seems to be an observation in 1890 (Taylor 1979). Surveys by Hamilton (1894) found none.
The last specimen was collected by de Marolles in 1844 (Voisin and Voisin 1995).

The last accounts of wild birds were from 1775, and birds were not mentioned by Bory in 1804, so it may have been hunted to extinction in the wild by then. A captive bird survived in the King of Bavaria's menagerie until at least 1834 (BirdLife International 2011).
Photographed at the nest in 1927, the last observation was in 1928 (Olsen 2008). Repeated searches since have found none.
The taxon went extinct around 1900 (Fuller 2000).
The last record was of a bird procured from locals in 1875. It is thought that the last few individuals were wiped out by intense cyclones in 1876 (Cheke 1987).
It was last recorded on Mahé in 1893, when Abbott shot a specimen (Skerrett and Disley 2011), and extinct by 1906 when Nicoll visited the islands (BirdLife International 2011).
No confirmed sightings sibce 1949

The species went extinct in the wild in the mid-19th century on Norfolk Island, although it may have persisted a little longer on nearby Phillip Island. The last recorded living bird was in captivity in London in 1851(Garnett et al. 2011). It was not recorded on searches of the island in 1908 (Hull 1909).

Authority: Rasmussen, Allen, Collar, de Meule Meester, Hutchinson, Jakosalem, Kennedy, Lambert & Paguntalan, 2012
Rasmussen, Allen, Collar, de Meule Meester, Hutchinson, Jakosalem, Kennedy, Lambert & Paguntalan, 2012

Former distribution: North I, South Island, New Zealand
Justification notes2: The North Island taxon is thought to have gone extinct around 1890 (A. J. D. Tennyson in litt. 2011), while the South island taxon had a last confirmed record from 1914 (Tennyson and Martinson 2006).

The five known specimens were collected during 1840–1850. In 1882, Stejneger was told by the island's residents that the last birds had disappeared about 30 years before (BirdLife International 2011).
The species was present in 1800 (Hindwood 1965), but not detected in 1840 (Moore 1985).

Common name: Astrolabe Nightingale Reed-warbler Acrocephalus luscinius astrolabii
Justification notes2: The two type specimens were collected during Second Antarctic Expedition 1838–1839 (Kennerley and Pearson 2010). There do not appear to have been any further records of the subspecies.
The taxon became extinct between 1916 and 1923 (BirdLife International 2011).

Common name: Pagan Nightingale Reed-warbler Acrocephalus luscinius yamashinae
Justification notes2: Became extinct on Pagan, to which it was confined, before 1981 (Bairlein et al. 2006). Local people stated that it persisted until the 1960s, but intensive searches in the late 1970s and early 1980s confirmed its extinction (Tenorio et al. 1979, Reichel et al. 1992).
